Description ( holotype , male). Body length 3.3 mm . Body reddish, pronotal disc darker, reddish brown, elytra unicoloured; legs and antennae reddish.
Male characters. Sternum VII nearly simple. Tergum VIII and aedeagus as in Figs 33, 34 .

Variation. Body length (♂ ♀ ) 2.7–3.7 mm ; some specimens with nearly unicolorous, whitish to pale reddish scales on elytra, brownish marking may be both absent and conspicuous; pronotal horn in the specimens from Queensland mostly subtriangular, with less projecting posterior angles ( Fig. 148 ).

subSubSection.paragraph:
Differential diagnosis.
Mecynotarsus bullatus
sp. nov. is undoubtedly close to
M. hirtipennis
sp. nov. as suggested by similarity of both external (triangular pronotal horn, semicircular crest rim, numerous tactile setae), and male characters. Its specimens are usually larger and more robust than those of the latter species, and differ especially by the longer, denser and somewhat double setation of the pronotal disc, with longer scales rather subdecumbent and somewhat overlapping shorter appressed scales, by the more robust antennae (basal antennomeres), and by the evenly narrowing, arcuately divergent and apically pointed parameres.

Etymology. The Latin adjective,
bullatus
, - a, -um (= bubble-like); named in reference to the peculiar rounded shape of horn crest rim.
Distribution. Australia : Queensland , Northern Territory , Western Australia .
